#Hi @zhangming-m the "samples" here mean the number of random draws from a probability distribution (the posterior distribution). It is a different concept than the number of individuals in a vcf file which is sometimes also referred to as "sample". So when you set 20 samples you have 20 ARGs drawn from the posterior distribution, and likewise for 100. The good way to work with posterior sampling methods is to aggregate information from these samples (ARGs), for example compute summary statistics from all samples and then average them. Or if you prefer simpler method which only outputs one estimate, tsinfer(https://tskit.dev/tsinfer/docs/stable/tutorial.html) and Relate(https://myersgroup.github.io/relate/) are also good options.